04448nam a22005655i 9781438494197DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384941977 a10.1515/97814384941972doi  a(DE-B1597)681663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1995.9.Y54b.C676 2023 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.430899242231 aCorne, Jonah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYiddish Cinema :bThe Drama of Troubled Communication /cMonika Vrečar, Jonah Corne. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (362 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 44  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series, Horizons of Cinema00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- t“The structure of communication is the infrastructure of human reality” -- tPowers of Music -- tDiscourse and Dialogue -- tThe Mass Media Family -- tThe Battle of the Books -- tMotherhood, Migration, and the Asylum -- t“Silence which is communication” -- tGroundlessness I (The Nation against the Jew) -- tGroundlessness II (Among the DPs) -- tMediating the Mystical -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Jonah Corne and Monika Vrečar offer a conceptually innovative reexamination of Yiddish cinema, a crucial yet little-known diasporic phenomenon that enjoyed its "golden age" in the mid- to late 1930s. Yiddish cinema, they argue, exhibits a distinctive fascination with media forms, technologies, and institutions, and with relationality writ large. What stands behind this communication obsession, as it might be understood, is the films' engagement both with Judaic ideals and with a series of Jewish sociohistorical predicaments of troubled communication (immigration, displacement, the breakdown of tradition, and so on) that the films seek to reflect. Accordingly, the authors create a resonant conversation between Yiddish cinema, populated by an endless procession of disconnected characters ardently striving to rejoin the world of communication, and the brilliant yet underappreciated ideas of pioneering Czech-Jewish media theorist Vilém Flusser (1920–1991), who escaped Nazi persecution and built the first part of his intellectual career in Brazil. Indeed, the authors claim that the popular art of Yiddish cinema articulates in dramatic terms a version of the central Flusserian hypothesis that "the structure of communication is the infrastructure of human reality" and, by doing so, embodies a remarkable Jewish media theory "from below." Films discussed include The Wandering Jew (1933), The Dybbuk (1937), Where is My Child? (1937), A Little Letter to Mother (1938), Kol Nidre (1939), Motel the Operator (1939), Tevye (1939), The Living Orphan (1939), and Long Is the Road (1948).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in motion pictures. 0aMass media in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictures, YiddishxHistory. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aVrečar, Monika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849419740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494197/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles